               <t:note>
                  <t:ab type="description">Gorgorā is a peninsula on the north of the Lake<t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC5888Tana">Ṭānā</t:placeName>. It is <t:width>12 km</t:width> wide in its
                     southern part and stands on a strategical location, an elevated rocky
                     promontory overlooking the lake and next to a series of islands suitable for
                     providing shelter. The peninsula is located in today's <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1426Amhara">ʾAmhārā</t:placeName> Regional State while it once formed
                     part of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2481Dambey">Dambǝyā</t:placeName>.
                     Gorgorā gained its prominence under the Jesuits as a missionary residence and a
                     major Catholic church thanks to a land grant offered by <t:roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</t:roleName>
                     <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9038Susenyos">Susǝnyos</t:persName> in <t:date>1607</t:date>. In
                        <t:date>1611</t:date>, <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9038Susenyos">Susǝnyos</t:persName>
                     established a <t:placeName>katamā</t:placeName> in Gorgorā and in <t:date>1621</t:date>
                     he asked the Jesuits to build a royal palace to the south-west, in an area that
                     became known as <t:placeName>New Gorgorā</t:placeName>. After the restoration of
                     Orthodoxy, <t:placeName>New Gorgorā</t:placeName> was the first residence to be
                     abandoned by the missionaries and, in <t:date>1665</t:date>, <t:roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</t:roleName>
                     <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</t:persName> ordered the burning of the
                     "books of Franks". The Italians seized the Gorgorā peninsula on <t:date>14 April
                        1936</t:date> and in <t:date>1938</t:date> inaugurated the <t:placeName>Faro della
                        Conquista</t:placeName> on the <t:placeName>Vetta Mussolini</t:placeName>.</t:ab>
               </t:note>
            </t:place>
            
         </t:listPlace>
      </t:body>
   </t:text></TEI>